name: Autotask Helpdesk
description: Add an Autotask Helpdesk Instance to connect your existing Autotask account to the Helpdesk Hub, allowing you to manage your incidents, priorities, statuses, users, etc. across multiple Help Desk Elements. You will need your Autotask Helpdesk account information to add an instance.
configDescription: If you do not have an Autotask.com account, you can create one at Autotask CRM Signup

configuration.name: Allow Select Fields parameter
configuration.description: Enables use of global fields query parameter to filter response to only specified fields. This will override any existing vendor functionality on the connector

configuration.name: Event Notification Subscription ID
configuration.description: The subscription ID for the webhook events subscription

configuration.name: Filter null values from the response
configuration.description: Used to enable/disable filtering of null values from the responses.

configuration.name: Default select fields
configuration.description: Generic map used to specify default fields for bulk download and GET /all requests. Each key should be the canonical objectName and values may be specified as a comma-delimited string or a list of strings

configuration.name: Integration Key Sent to AutoTask on all api Calls via CE
configuration.description: Integration key sent to AutoTask on all api calls via CE

configuration.name: Event poller refresh interval
configuration.description: Used for how often to poll the application (in minutes)

configuration.name: Event Poller Objects|URL
configuration.description: An element poling Objects and URL used for event notifications from provider, if URL is not mentioned then it uses the default URL for polling for that object, format should be objectname|url

configuration.name: Event Notification Callback URL
configuration.description: An application callback URL used for event notifications from Autotask and Cloud Elements, e.g., Incidents created , etc.

configuration.name: Callback Notification Signature Key
configuration.description: A key used to generate a validation hash header of the event/bulk notification webhook callback payload

resources.description: Search for accounts

parameters.name: where
parameters.description: The CEQL search expression, or the where clause, without the WHERE keyword, in a typical SQL query. For example, to search for accounts last modified on or after 'Jan 15, 2014', the search expression will be where=lastModifiedDate>='2014-01-15T00:00:00.000Z'. When this parameter is omitted, all accounts are returned in a paginated fashion.

parameters.name: includeDeleted
parameters.description: Specify if deleted accounts should be included in the search.

parameters.name: page
parameters.description: The page number. Defaults to 1 if not provided

parameters.name: nextPage
parameters.description: The token or link for getting the next page. This type of paging is a cursor based paging, where you have to start at the beginning and traverse the result set. For large result sets, this can be significantly faster than using 'page''

parameters.name: pageSize
parameters.description: The page size. Defaults to 200 if not provided. Maximum of 5000

resources.description:
Search for attachments in the help desk system, using the provided CEQL search expression. The search expression in CEQL is the WHERE clause in a typical SQL query, but without the WHERE keyword. For example, to search for all attachments whose fileName contains the word 'ultraround', the search expression parameter will be where=fileName='%ultraround%'. Performing a search without these parameters will not return any results.

If a value of true is specified for the includeDeleted flag, then any soft-deleted records will also be considered in the searched records.

parameters.name: where
parameters.description: The CEQL search expression, or the where clause, without the WHERE keyword, in a typical SQL query. For example, to search for attachments with file name information.txt the search expression will be where=title='information.txt'. When this parameter is omitted, all attachments are returned in a paginated fashion.

parameters.name: includeDeleted
parameters.description: Specify if deleted attachments should be included in the search.

parameters.name: pageSize
parameters.description: The number of results to return per page

parameters.name: nextPage
parameters.description: The token or link for getting the next page. This type of paging is a cursor based paging, where you have to start at the beginning and traverse the result set. For large result sets, this can be significantly faster than using 'page''

resources.description:
Returns a list of objects based on a set of search parameters.  Here is an example query:  select id, name			(Fields of that Object)
from contactX			(Name of Object)
where name like '%foo%' 	(Search Expression)
or name like '%bar%;		(Search Expression continued)
order by createdDate 		(Order of Search)
limit 10 			(How Many Results to Display)
offset 0 			(Where to start in the list of objects)
In this example, I am querying a list of objects from contactX containing the fields id and name where the name contains foo or bar.  The results will be in a list of 10 organized by the date they were created, starting with the earliest.

parameters.name: q
parameters.description: The search query (i.e. select id, name from contact where name like '%foo' limit 10 offset 0

resources.description:
Retrieve a user or users in the help desk system, using the provided object name and CEQL search expression. The search expression in CEQL is the WHERE clause in a typical SQL query, but without the WHERE keyword. For example, to search for all users whose name contains the word 'smith', the search expression parameter will be where=name='%smith%'. Performing a search without these parameters will not return any results.

If a value of true is specified for the includeDeleted flag, then any soft-deleted records will also be considered in the searched records.

parameters.name: where
parameters.description: The CEQL search expression, or the where clause, without the WHERE keyword, in a typical SQL query. For example, to search for users with contactId, the search expression will be where=contactID = 29683588. When this parameter is omitted, all users are returned in a paginated fashion.

parameters.name: includeDeleted
parameters.description: Specify if deleted users should be included in the search.

parameters.name: pageSize
parameters.description: The number of results to return per page

parameters.name: nextPage
parameters.description: The token or link for getting the next page. This type of paging is a cursor based paging, where you have to start at the beginning and traverse the result set. For large result sets, this can be significantly faster than using 'page''

parameters.name: page
parameters.description: The one-indexed page for paginated items (e.g. '2' begins with the third item)
